  "prompt": "The current year is 2014. Why is this the 21st century and not the 20th century?",
  "response": "The way we number centuries is based on the Gregorian calendar, and it can be a bit counterintuitive. Here's why:\n\n- The **1st century** started in the year **1** and ended in the year **100**.\n- The **2nd century** started in **101** and ended in **200**.\n- This pattern continues, so the **21st century** started in **2001** and will end in **2100**.\n\nSince the current year is **2014**, it falls within the range of 2001\u20132100, which is the **21st century**. The **20th century**, on the other hand, was from 1901 to 2000.\n\nThe confusion often arises because people associate the \"20\" in \"20th century\" with the years starting with 20 (like 2000, 2001, etc.), but in reality, the century number is one ahead of the year marker. For example, the \"21\" in \"21st century\" corresponds to the years **2001\u20132100**. \n\nSo, **2014** is in the **21st century** because it is part of the 2001\u20132100 range.",
